paragraphs.title: Zeppelin Demo Notebook 3
paragraphs.text:
%md
Demonstrate loading data from S3, using an [AWS Glue Data Catalog](https://aws.amazon.com/glue/features/).
The AWS Glue Data Catalog is a persistent metadata store for all data assets, regardless of where they are located.
Using the Data Catalog reduces the amount of code we need to write, to read data into a Spark DataFrame or convert to temporary view.

paragraphs.title: AWS Glue Crawlers
paragraphs.text:
%md
Run each of the seven AWS Glue Crawlers, one time each before continuing.

```%sh
aws glue start-crawler --name bakery-transactions-crawler
aws glue start-crawler --name movie-ratings-crawler
```

paragraphs.title: Import Python Packages
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
from pyspark import SparkFiles
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType, DateType

paragraphs.title: Show AWS Glue Data Catalog Database Tables
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
spark.sql("show databases").show(10, False)
spark.sql("use zeppelin_demo")
spark.sql("show tables in zeppelin_demo").show(10, False)

# Refresh tables since it might have changed due to experimentation
# Spark SQL caches Parquet metadata for better performance
spark.catalog.refreshTable("movies_parquet_100k")
spark.catalog.refreshTable("ratings_parquet_100k")

paragraphs.title: Create DataFrame from Spark SQL Query
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
ratings_df = spark.sql("SELECT movieId, rating, userId, CAST(timestamp as timestamp) as dateTime " +
                      "FROM ratings_parquet_100k " +
                      "ORDER BY movieId, rating, userId")

print("DataFrame rows: %d" % ratings_df.count())
ratings_df.show(10, False)

paragraphs.title: Create DataFrame from Spark SQL Query
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
top_movies_df = spark.sql("SELECT m.title, CAST(AVG(r.rating) AS DECIMAL(4,3)) as avg_rating, COUNT(r.rating) as cnt_ratings " +
                          "FROM ratings_parquet_100k r " +
                          "JOIN movies_parquet_100k m ON (r.movieId = m.movieId) " +
                          "GROUP BY m.title " +
                          "ORDER BY avg_rating DESC, cnt_ratings DESC, m.title ASC")
                        
top_movies_df = top_movies_df.filter(top_movies_df.cnt_ratings >= 25)

print("DataFrame rows: %d" % top_movies_df.count())
print("Top 10 Movies")
top_movies_df.show(10, False)

paragraphs.title: Native Zeppelin Visualization Based on SQL Query
paragraphs.text:
%sql
WITH tmp_table AS (
    SELECT m.title, AVG(r.rating) as avg_rating, COUNT(r.rating) as cnt_ratings
    FROM ratings_parquet_100k r
    JOIN movies_parquet_100k m ON (r.movieId = m.movieId)
    GROUP BY m.title)
    
SELECT title, CAST(avg_rating AS DECIMAL(38,2)), cnt_ratings
FROM tmp_table
WHERE avg_rating >= ${avgRatingMin=4} AND cnt_ratings >= ${RatingsMin=2}
ORDER BY avg_rating ASC, cnt_ratings DESC, title ASC
LIMIT 25
